(This etymology suffers from the fact that it includes a reconstructed *b, which is extremely rare in Proto-Indo-European. Yet according to [[Indogermanisches etymologisches Wörterbuch|Pokorny]] it is well distributed, with additional apparent cognates in Slavic, British and Lithuanian.<ref>
[http://starling.rinet.ru/cgi-bin/response.cgi?root=config&morpho=0&basename=%5Cdata%5Cie%5Cpokorny&first=921 ''Indogermanisches etymologisches Wörterbuch''] (see [[Indogermanisches etymologisches Wörterbuch|article]]), by [[Julius Pokorny]]; database on starling.rinet.ru. See also English version at [http://dnghu.org/indoeuropean.html Indo-European Etymological Dictionary - Indogermanisches Etymologisches Woerterbuch (JPokorny)]. Both accessed 2013-08-09.
