The use of a dog is uncertain,<ref>
{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=Cerberus|title= Cerberus|publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary|first=Douglas|last=Harper|accessdate=2008-10-21}}
</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://colet.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/chuck/woodhouse_pages.pl?page_num=1005|title=Woodhouse's English-Greek Dictionary|publisher= University of Chicago Library|accessdate=2008-10-21}}
</ref> although mythologists have speculated that the association was first made in the city of Trikarenos in Phliasia.<ref name="maurice-7">
{{cite book|title=Cerberus the Dog of Hades|first=Maurice|last= Bloomfield|year=2003|publisher=[[Kessinger Publishing]]|isbn=0766130207|page=7}}
</ref> Bruce Lincoln (1991),<ref>{{cite book|last=Lincoln|first=Bruce|title=Death, war, and sacrifice: studies in ideology and practice|year=1991|publisher=University of Chicago Press|location=Chicago|isbn=9780226481999|pages=289}}</ref> among others, critiques this etymology; and Ogden (2013)<ref>{{cite book|last=Ogden|first=Daniel|title= Drakon: Dragon Myth and Serpent Cult in the Greek and Roman Worlds|year=2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=0199557322|pages=105}}</ref> refers to it as "dismissed".

Lincoln notes a similarity between Cerberus and the [[Norse mythology|Norse mythological]] dog [[Garmr]], relating both names to a Proto-Indo-European root ''*ger-'' "to growl" (perhaps with the suffixes ''-*m/*b'' and ''-*r''). However, as Ogden observes, this analysis actually requires ''Cerberus'' and ''Garmr'' to be derived from two ''different'' Indo-European roots (*''ger-'' and *''gher-'' respectively), and so does not actually establish a relationship between the two names.

==Explanations==
There have been many attempts to explain the depiction of Cerberus. A 2nd century CE Greek known as [[Heraclitus the paradoxographer]]--- not to be confused with the 5th century BCE Greek philosopher [[Heraclitus]]--- claimed [[Euhemerus|Euhemeristically]] that Cerberus had two pups which were never away from their father, and that Cerberus was in fact a normal (though very large) dog, but that artists incorporating the two pups into their work made it appear as if his two children were in fact extra heads.<ref>{{cite book|title=Περὶ ἀπίστων|author=Heraclitus|page=331}}</ref> Classical historians have dismissed Heraclitus the paradoxographer's explanation as "feeble".<ref name="maurice-7">{{cite book|title=Cerberus the Dog of Hades|first=Maurice|last= Bloomfield|year=2003|publisher=[[Kessinger Publishing]]|isbn=0-7661-3020-7|page=7}}</ref> Mythologers have speculated that if Cerberus was given his name in Trikarenos it could be interpreted as "three karenos".<ref name="maurice-7"/> Certain experts believe that the monster was inspired by the [[golden jackal]].<ref name="GJ">{{cite web|title=Golden Jackal|work= |publisher=Canids.org|url=http://www.canids.org/species/Golden_jackal.pdf|accessdate=2007-08-15}}</ref>

